'''Macaquitos''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: '''Los Macaquinhos''') is a [[Spanish Language]] [[racist]] reference used at the first half of the 20th century by [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[football (soccer)|football]] fans against [[Brazil|Brazilians]] within the [[Argentina and Brazil football rivalry]]. The [[pejorative]] term was an association of the [[mulato]] race of many Brazilian football players with [[monkey]]s.

Some people in Brazil affirm that the term is much older than football rivalry, with its origins in the [[War of Paraguay]], when Argentine soldiers referred to their Brazilian counterparts as monkeys. 

The first time the word was quoted was in 1920 after a friendly match that [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] won 3-1 against [[Brazil national football team]]. It was again used by Argentine fans in several of the following matches, but was desused before 1950. Currently, [[yellow press]] sometime take advantage of the lost expression to inrcease the sports rivalry, such as the [[Diario Olé]] 1996 controversial headline "Let the macacos come" (''Que vengan los macacos''), when Argentina's rival for the final match of the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|gold medal]] was to be decided between Brazil and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]. Critics to such headline arose both in Argentina and Brazil. Nigeria obtained the golden medal, while Argentine got the silver and Brazil the bronze.

